  issn                       = {0254-3737},
  month                      = {{WIN}},
  number                     = {1},
  pages                      = {141-155},
  volume                     = {37},
  abstract                   = {{This study explores the effects of tax incentives for charitable
   contributions concerning taxpayers' socioeconomic characteristics,
   religion, and political preference. Using South Korean household-level
   panel data, we regard people from a wide range of demographics and
   religious and political groups as our research subject. We obtain the
   following results: (1) Controlling for religious and political
   preferences enhances the estimation result. (2) Taxpayers practicing
   Protestantism do not significantly respond to tax incentives, although
   they are the most philanthropic group of all religious groups studied.
   (3) Political preference significantly affects donation behavior,
   wherein conservatives react less significantly to tax incentives than
   progressives. Our results provide evidence that giving intention is not
   only practice-driven but also ideology-driven.}},
